Uses satellite constellations in Low Earth Orbit (LEO) to deliver global connectivity

Provides high-speed, low-latency internet to remote and underserved areas

Operates without ground cables; satellites act as wireless routers in space

Data transmission path: User antenna ‚Üí Satellite ‚Üí Satellite ‚Üí Ground hub

Signals travel in milliseconds via laser inter-satellite links (ISLs) and ground stations

Major Projects:

Starlink (SpaceX)

OneWeb

Amazon‚Äôs Project Kuiper

Benefits:

Coverage for rural, oceanic, and disaster-affected regions

Enables education, healthcare, and communication in remote zones

Reduces dependence on fiber-optic infrastructure

Challenges:

Orbital congestion and space debris risk

High operational cost and maintenance

Signal interference and regulatory issues

Impact:

Aims to make global internet access universal, turning connectivity into a basic human right

üåê Space Networks (TDRS & LCRD)
TDRS ‚Äì Tracking and Data Relay Satellite System:

Developed and operated by NASA

Geostationary satellite network providing real-time communication with spacecraft

Continuous coverage for ISS, Hubble, and other low-orbit missions

Data path: Spacecraft ‚Üí TDRS satellite ‚Üí Ground terminal

Eliminates need for direct line-of-sight passes

Handles telemetry, tracking, command, and data transmission

Positioned ~35,786 km above Earth in geostationary orbit (GEO)

LCRD ‚Äì Laser Communications Relay Demonstration:

NASA mission testing laser (optical) communication in space

Uses laser light instead of radio waves

Up to 100√ó faster data rates than traditional RF systems

Smaller antennas, lower interference, higher security

Demonstrates efficient transmission of high-resolution data, images, and videos

Prepares for deep-space optical communication

Works with TDRS to evolve high-speed space communication networks

üåå Artificial Gravity & Microgravity
Microgravity Effects:

Near weightlessness experienced by astronauts

Long exposure causes:

Muscle atrophy

Bone density reduction

Cardiovascular weakening

Fluid redistribution affecting vision and balance

Disorientation and sleep difficulties

Serious risks for long-duration missions (e.g., Mars)

Artificial Gravity Concept:

Produced by centrifugal force from rotation (not real gravity)

Formula: a = œâ¬≤ √ó r (a = artificial gravity, œâ = angular velocity, r = radius)

Increasing radius allows slower, comfortable rotation

Too-fast rotation causes Coriolis effects (dizziness, nausea)

Design Methods:

Rotating spacecraft: entire spacecraft spins slowly

Centrifugal habitats: only a ring or section spins

Tethered systems: two modules connected by a cable rotate around center of mass

Research & Development:

NASA, ESA, and JAXA experiment with small centrifuges

JAXA‚Äôs Kibo module on ISS studies partial gravity on organisms

Stanford Torus and O‚ÄôNeill Cylinder are theoretical rotating habitat models

Lunar Gateway and future Mars missions may include artificial gravity modules

Challenges:

Structural stress from constant rotation

High energy demand for spin-up and stabilization

Maintaining balance and orientation control

Human adaptation to partial or rotating gravity

Future Outlook:

Artificial gravity essential for long-term human survival in space

Enables healthier, sustainable missions to Mars and beyond

Key step toward building livable habitats beyond Earth"
